1 Frankenstein

Frankenstein by Mary Shelly is a story of ambition, parenthood, empathy, revenge, and tragidy. The story chronicles the journey of Victor Frankenstein, a medical student from Geneva, as he persues his quest to create life and the consequences that follow. The book is told from three different perspectives: Frankenstein who is the central figure of the book, The Monster Frankenseins creation, and Captain Robert Walton who literaly bookends the story.

This project will be doing Text Analysis on the book as a whole and each characters Point of View (POV). It will be interesting to see the word usage from observing the book as a whole as well as each characters perspective to see if there are dramatic differences in vocabullary.

1.1 Parsing and Web Scraping

In order to even perform Text Analysis we need the actual text. Ive pulled text from The Gutenberg Project, a site dedicated to providing free e-books online for anyone whos interested.

The key to this project is not only to be able to parse the book, but also to be able to keep the structure of the book such as the chapters. To do this I took note of where the chapters were located in the text by looking for h2 tags. I would then find what lines contained these chapter titles and segment the entire book between these tags. I utilized a helper script file, TextAnalysis_SupportFile.R, that does a lot of the heavy lifting and that I utilize throughout this project.

Once I was able to collect the book into a large list of strings, where each index represented a chapter, I was able to make subsets of the book that represented the three different POVs in the book; Frankenstein, The Monster, and The Captain.

We see from looking at the top most used words in the book that there are some obvious themes: Identity, Family, and Life. All three of these themes can be wrapped up in a larger theme of Empathy.

The words one, man, mind are used primarly to create an Identity of a character. Who are they? What do they value? What are there personalities, drives, and ambitions?

Father and Elizabeth are referring to Victors Father, Alphonse Frankenstein, and Elizabeth Lavenza, Victors adopted sister and wife (it was 1818 so go figure). The Frankenstein Family is very important to Victor as it becomes his goal to protect his family from the monster he created. Whenever someone in the family dies from the creature the tragidy it creates ripples and tears through the family with devastating effect; Shellys life was also filled with tragedy and loss so making parallels between authors family tragedy and her characters is plain to see. One very interesting note: the monster NEVER calls Victor Frankenstein Father (I read the book to prep for this project), the monster only ever refers to him as creator which is more reverant placeholder for Father.

Eyes and Life are the words that best fall under the, well, Life category. The usage of the words life is most commonly used to describe as a remarkable gift as well as unending burden that many characters fail to carry. Eyes are often described as windows of the soul for good reason, they are what we use to observe the world and to visually connect with others. The Monsters watery eyes is one of the key features that makes Victor horrified of what he created when they open, and the same eyes that this essentially newborn uses to observe this new world to him.

Words that I thought would be more prevelant going into this analysis was words focused on Death, but the closest word that would fall under that category is night. Words like death are sparingly used in the book. When people die in the book theyre mostly described as lifeless; this may have been the author viewing death as more of an absence of life than a state of being.

Some words that are miscaleneous are words like might which in the book is often used to describe possible events and to physical strength of individuals, this is also similar for the word will.

There is a lot to disect here, but Ill focus on some of the more important 2-Grams:

  • old man is often a place holder for Victors Father, and other fatherly figures. Seeing how often Father was used earlier this isnt all that surpising. This is in contrast with lesser used term young man which is manily used to describe innocense

  • native country is said a lot through the book, as home is very important to characters as thats where their family resides. Victor for example misses Geneva a lot through out the book and is often homesick until the end where it only reminds him of heartbreak.

  • dear victor is often used as the opening to letters addressed to Victor. Most of the letters are from Elizabeth, who as mentioned earlier is very important to Frankenstein.

  • natural philosophy is used almost entirely in place of the word science. Science is said occasionally through out the book, but back in 1818 it probably wasnt used as much as commonly as natural philosophy. This is quite ironic considering this is the first major example of science fiction ever written.

  • mr kirwin, de lacey are names of characters in the book. Mr Kirwin is the magistrate who accuses Victor for murder, and De Lacey is the bling old man who the monster tries to befriend.

  • mont blanc is very important to Victor as it is the mountain that represents home to him as well as the first place the Victor and The Monster confront each other.

By the nature of 3-Grams the frequency of each phrase is much smaller than the 2-Grams:

  • Similary to dear victor mrs saville england is the opening of the 4 letters sent by Captain Robert Walton at the beginning of the book.

  • There are refrences used to describe Victors home or his arrival of home such as return native country and surrounded mountains ice. Geneva is located in Switzerland, which is known for being mountainous and snowy.

  • Frankensteins story spans around 6 years and this can be seen by usage of summer passed away, nearly two months, since left us, and six years passed.

  • This was a horror novel in 1818 and you can see that with the 3-Grams figure man distance, hour state mind, fiend grasp neck. Though their usage is very low you can tell that this book is haunted by mystery, tension, and violence.

From observing the TF-IDF scores I would disagree on some of these words indeed being important. In short the higher the TF-IDF score the more important that word is. The words I would disagree with are: gales, latitude, renovating, stiff, and springing.

However, the rest of the scores I would say are pretty accurate especially felix, turk, and safie. Felix is the son of the blind man living in the cottage I mentioned earlier, and Safie is the Turkish woman that Felix proposes to. The Monster learns about the world from observing Felix and Safie, and its their relationship to each other that gives The Monster the idea to ask Victor to make him a wife.

I would say the rest of the words are only of marginally significance. england is visited durring Victors travels and where the Captain is from. voyage likely refers to the Voyage that the Captain is on to explore the Arctic. Most of the words really only have high scores from two chapters by looking at their individual total_words, so it seems there maybe some accidental weight boosting going on.

5 Conclusion

From doing this analysis Ive determined each narrator in the book has different word choice and focuses on different aspects of the themes mentioned earlier. Victor is more family and ambition focused, The Monster is an innocent creature and wants to be part of humanity despite being shunned by it, and The Captain is someone desperate to have company in an abysmal wasteland. There is some overlap with some words, but thats likely due to the author wanting to relate an underlying theme.

Its also somewhat apparent that certain POVs somewhat skewed the overall analysis of the book. Most of the word counts and n-Grams were very similar to the ones found in Victor Frankensteins POV which isnt exactly surprising since the book is named after him. Breaking the book up by narrator really helped gain insight into how each character was different from one another.

5.1 Further Work

I would like to apply what Ive done here to other books by Mary Shelly but given how unstable the Gutenbergs style by being constantly updated that wouldve been a nightmare to make sure a parser could be consistent across the site. It would probably be best to download the html files and analize them locally instead.

I would also like to explore sentiment analysis the same way I explored text analysis, as it wouldve been very interesting to see if the intent of the narrator changes by chapter.
